commits.commitMessage:
Change Leaf's process for tagging latest

Leaf's tagging process for latest is now based on an identifier and
their tags. So, packages will now be compared only to other packages
that share the same identifier and the same tags. This allows better
differentiation between image types, i.e. LXSWI and SWI9X07Y or
onlycap, signed and unsigned. As well as, allow each type to have a
latest version.

Resolves: LETOOLS-1145
Change-Id: I59864a904784a7a76947777836b2e0427e62ba42
commits.subject: Change Leaf's process for tagging latest

comments.message: Translate this description into unit tests in the source code.
Same as other comment, the unit tests I stated already cover this scenario.
Could you design some unit tests for tags.py? Put into leaf/tests/
We already have unit tests like test_manifest in TestRenderingAnsi, TestRenderingAnsiQuiet, TestRendering, and TestRenderingAnsiVerbose testing for tags.

Unit test should be self explanory, target unit is as smallest as possible. Unfortunately, test_manifest looks like a more feature testing in this case. Covered tags.py implicitly. If we can have test_tags.py to directly verify tags.py, that would be better.
Why do both of these packages have latest?

They are latest due to the change in how we tag latest. When determining what is latest, a package is compared to against package with the same identifier and in the same tag group. So in this case, "Container-A_1.0" is compared to packages with identifier "container-A" and tag "foo" and since there are no other packages with foo, it is then considered latest. This is synonymous to thinking container-A is an SDK package for wp76xx, foo could be onlycap and bar could be signed, we want to tag them each as latest, because they are the latest version of their respective variations.

In continuation of previous comment, the onlycap packages would only compare against other packages with onlycap and vice versa with signed. With the old latest tagging process we would encounter a scenario where the onlycap SDK was the latest to be released and if a user used a query like "leaf search SDK -t wp76xx -t latest" the onlycap package would be the only package to be returned, which is incorrect, we should have the latest version of each variation to be returned (signed, onlycap, unsigned). The new tagging process would avoid this.

it was initially defined by LeafConstants.CACHE_SIZE_MAX and is not configurable
Overall we should use positive logic (leaf.cache.autoclean) instead of the other way around.
Can we get some feedback once the action has been completed such as "Cache has been cleaned"

comments.message: Would it also support things more complex, such as LXSWI2.5-3.0.rc1 , SWI9X28A_00.01.02.03 ... ?
Could you give me some tricky examples with theses versions?

Well, I guess nothing too tricky, it's just a bit different in term of numbering.

True statements:

LXSWI2.5-3.0 > LXSWI2.5-3.0.rc1
LXSWI2.5-4.0 > LXSWI2.5-3.0
LXSWI2.5-3.1 > LXSWI2.5-3.0
LXSWI2.7-1.0 > LXSWI2.5-11.0

SWI9X28A_00.02.00.00 > SWI9X28A_00.01.02.03
SWI9X28A_00.01.02.03 > SWI9X28A_00.01.02.02

Now for Legato it's actually a bit tricky:
16.10.0.m3.rc1 > 16.10.0
... arg I don't have much examples at hand right now.
normally there shouldn't be any space here around =, no?

We setup black as the default code formatter in leaf because black is the most strict formatter available and we've had enough code formatting endless discussions on the team :)
So we are using black implemented conventions.
The one and only convention we were ok to change is line length, must be 160 or 200 ... 

Black adds spaces before and after the '=' if you specify the type of the argument as *implicit_zero: bool = False*, if you don't specify the type, black does not add spaces *implicit_zero=False*.
To improve the general code quality, we try to specify parameter types for *public* APIs, so we have spaces.
Oh I see, I was also thinking of black but didn't knew the difference with the explicit types.

comments.message:
Leaf (end so leaf shell) is agnostic of the packages it installs and uses.
You shouldn't reference this variable here.

Moreover, to respect leaf shell behavior, we would need an alternative script that unset configured variables before switching the active profile, otherwise the environment won't be up to date.

Finally, build.sh is not part of the built Legato packages at the moment.
I've created LETOOLS-841 to handle this, and export in the package manifest the variables coming from config.sh

Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)

The retry mechanism has a *continue* mode to restart the download where it stopped.
Have you tried your *continue* mode implementation?
We may need a unit test to test it, can you imagine a scenario we could implement in the unit tests?

Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)

> Patch Set 4:
> 
> (1 comment)
> 
> The retry mechanism has a *continue* mode to restart the download where it stopped.
> Have you tried your *continue* mode implementation?
> We may need a unit test to test it, can you imagine a scenario we could implement in the unit tests?

Not sure what you mean by "The retry mechanism has a *continue* mode to restart the download where it stopped.".
Here I did test by using tcpkill to kill active connections to get.legato as to retry.
But this requires to be root, and is overall not too easy to automatize.

One possibility to test the retry mechanism would be to create an http server (even if it only takes care of forwarding requests to an actual server like a proxy) so that we can kill/restart that server. That would allow us to do disconnections by controlling the server side.

comments.message: Please document these new entries in the leaf-colors page
Need to enumerate new possible keys in this list

Add a tip: "please check network connection, or remote URL"
+ add a "or " to the existing one
I can't see this exception if using an unknown package is used with *leaf setup -p* or *leaf udpate -p*

Both cause and error give this same message with this error
We probably don't need the "caused by" line

tip shall be different according to the used initial command
'leaf profile sync' is ok if package install was triggered by leaf setup/leaf update
'leaf package install package_name' must be suggested if it was triggered by package install package_name
Defines the color for hints on how to resolve errors

In some cases, tips can be shown even if no error occurs. So here is what I'll write :
=== tips

Defines the color for hints

=== tips_commands

Defines the color for commands in *tips*

does this print it to the terminal or to some log?

Reword: When set, will print a stack trace to <the screen, or log> when an error occurs

commits.commitMessage:
Add Colors to Commands, Tags and Log Messages

- Let it possible to use color ansi chars in outputs
- Add colorama as an optional python module in requirements
- Manage non tty usages (no color)
- Implement a theme module let the used setup its own colors/styles
- Use renderer for all command which have details output
  - leaf search
  - leaf package list
  - leaf remote list
  - leaf package deps
  - leaf status
  - leaf feature list
  - leaf profile list
- Remove useless code in logger
- Create/Improve tests for all formated commands and modules

Change-Id: I411775538c788374fa9f4fb4539707eb66aa7fd6
Resolves: LETOOLS-360
commits.subject: Add Colors to Commands, Tags and Log Messages

comments.message: don't see any update on the env command (gracefully!)
The code have been migrated to Renderer API keeping the exact same output in order to keep code coherent.

add [current] tag here as well, for terminals that don't support colors
Maybe only the current tag shall be colored, not the profile name
Maybe Fetched field is useless if remote is disabled

add [current] tag for terminal without colors.
Only the current tag shall be colored.

For more consistency, I wonder if this information shouldn't be put in a separated column, as for the default mode
An alternative could be to have a Properties column (like search -v), listing:
- sync value
- env vars
- packages

add [current] tag, for terminals that don't support colors
only the current tag shall be colored
Maybe highlight that this is a key name: <selected> or 'selected'

Please add some more documentation about other keys purpose:
<error>
<table_separator>
<remote_disabled>
<profile_current>

commits.commitMessage:
Rework package generation

- Use *tar* external tool to create leaf packages
- Can pass extra args to *tar* using --
- Can use -X for file exclusion
- Can use any tar option to achieve reproducible builds
- Remove --root-owner and --timestamps that can be handled as tar
  extra arguments
- By default generated packages are not compressed tar files
- Can use '-J', '-j' or '-z' as tar extra arg to get XZ/BZ2/GZ compression
- *tar* binary can be overridden using LEAF_TAR_BIN env var

As an example here is a command to have reproducible builds:
$ leaf repository pack \
    -i /path/to/package_1.0 -o myPackage.leaf -- \
    --mtime='Tue Oct  9 00:00:00 UTC 2018' \
    --sort=name \
    --owner=0 --group=0 --numeric-owner \
    .

Resolves: LETOOLS-587 LETOOLS-579
Change-Id: I52f975900371dfe5143c5085b4bb30a8e130e0ca
commits.subject: Rework package generation

commits.commitMessage:
Update *repository* command

- *pack*:
  - Add *--format* to specify a compression
  - Remove *--date*, manifest update handled by *manifest* subcommand
  - Add *--timestamp* to specify the timestamp of files stored in TAR archive
- *index*:
  - Add '--prettyprint' for json pretty printing (default is disabled,
    json is minified)
- *manifest*
  - new subcommand to generate a manifest
  - can append n layers of json files
  - can setup common attributes (name, version, requires ...)
  - can perform string replacement with env vars (format: #{USER})

Resolves: LETOOLS-525 LETOOLS-526
Change-Id: If777743c1bd2b3281699c7b67119ad11a36f5a20
commits.subject: Update *repository* command

comments.message:
we're displaying more than just the URLs.
Other information (read from repositories metadata) include:
* the repository description
* index build date

Maybe simply "display remotes information"
How about "display remote repository information" our customers aren't going to know what a remotes is. Shouldn't it also be remote? plurals in commands aren't really used.
search for development kits for your module
leaf is intended to be generic, and even doesn't have the concept of "module". Everything can be packed as a leaf package, without being related to a module.

That's fine, but we still need to give the users instructions that is not the internal implementation.  
"search for
displays all available packages (not just SDK packages)

leaf doesn't have the concept of "SDK".
It has the "master" package concept (boolean value in packages metadata) instead to know if the package shall be displayed in a simple search (master ones) or not (non-master ones).
If the "master" wording doesn't suit well, please can you suggest another one?
filter search results by meta-data tag

Results filtering can be done both on tags coming from metadata and on "dynamic" tags ("latest", "current", etc...)

Alternative wording: "filter search results matching with given tag"
filter search results with meta-data tag

comments.message: let's reuse the "[current]" wording (at the end of the line), with the appropriate style, as in previous implementation

THis new exception is nicer than previous implementation.
Maybe we could also have a boolean argument, with a default value not to change the default behaviour, to have a noException mode which returns NoneN
Add an argument to enable/disable Exception raising is a generally bad design. If the exception is not relevant in some context, it should be catch silently on the user side.

I don't like having this UI related method here, it should be part of the command.
The command needs to print info, it computes everything it needs and then give to the renderer.
If we want to display a new info in the status, we will need to update this method which is part of the API we aim to maintain.
Current profile is already printed. Check the glimpse in the comments of _toStringDefault and _toStringVerbose
Yes, in verbose, the current profile is printed, I was talking about this toStringQuiet method though.
My bad,  I did not see that your comment was for quiet mode. I'll ask @dpo

I thinks it's overkill and less maintainable just to manage a plural. The current version is clear and easy to modify. I don't want to factorize that. Moreover, sometimes letters are replaced in plural forms, not only added. So this proposed implementation will not works in theses cases (example: dependency, dependencies).

In facts the proposed implementation does work for those cases ;)
You can specify a suffix (by default s, 90% of the cases), but you can specify an alternative plural word.

Oh, again my bad, your function works.
I still think it's less readable/maintainable to write that:
profileLabel=plural(nbPf, "profile")
depsLabel=plural(nbDeps, "dependency", plur="dependencies")
than that:
profileLabel="profile" if nbPf <= 1 else "profiles"
depsLabel="dependency" if nbDeps <= 1 else "dependencies"
Also, the whole point of factoring code is to modify the code in only one place when the rule change. I don't think than the English grammar rules will change in a global manner (like "let's use a 'd' instead of a 's' or put this plural suffix at the beginning :-) )
Remove this line, this is a workspace cli test, we must not interfer using the package CLI
This changes show the limitation of testing the output, we should think od a way to handle this properly.

This is not an issue because it only change if the test code change. And the output generate itself and can be checked and validated instantly.
Trying to insert some intelligence/regex in theses output will only make it horrible to maintain. We need to keep the output generate itself for theses test.

Yes this pattern only changes if code changes, but if I add/remove a comment at the top of the source code, this file will change, even if the code hasn't modified, that is not good IMO.

I know you're not familiar with regex but there might be an alternative to solve this issue, I suggested to reflection to find one.

By the way, the env var to update the templates does not work with tox (or I couldn't make it work, but it is not documented), so it is not as easy as you think to generate the output.

Please don't make assumption about my regex's knowledge, i'm fine with it :-)
It just take way more time to edit an output file than to generate it and compare it using git.
Also I don't like the alternative (which is ignore a part of the line) because I want to check ALL potentials impact of my code changes on the output.

About tox, here is a way to pass some env var:
https://tox.readthedocs.io/en/latest/example/basic.html#passing-down-environment-variables

Add default configuration files skeleton

- For configuration file and theme configuration file, if no file found
in
  $HOME/.config/leaf/, then default configuration file (/etc/leaf/XXX)
aka
  skeleton file will be used
- Implement configuration file with layers for configuration file
  - A read only skeleton typically in /etc, shared with all system users
  - A user configuration file stored in $HOME/.config/leaf which

commits.commitMessage:
Implement GPG signature checking for remotes

- When adding a remote, a GPG fingerprint can be provided
- Legacy remotes can be added using '--insecure'
- When fetching remote content, the key is updated from sks servers pool
  to detect revoked keys or new subkeys.
- Remove *composite* remotes
- Clean some devel config files
- Index generation now detects dups with different artifacts

Resolves: LETOOLS-434 LETOOLS-435 LETOOLS-465
Change-Id: I73e921b6f459707b9c3c792b5b35f9172c0ef77b
commits.subject: Implement GPG signature checking for remotes

The security team's approved hash function list.  SHA1 has known vulnerabilities.

Patch Set 2:

After discussing this with Sébastien, we were thinking that the logic should look like this:

 - Download the packages.
 - Install the packages.
     - Run package install scripts.
 - Run sync scripts as a separate step.

Though I've been thinking about this and my main question here is that shouldn't sync scripts only be run during a sync operation?

Is the behaviour that we want to run the install scripts and then the sync scripts during an install?

Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)

The agreement is that sync steps are only run during a sync operation.

Install only runs install scripts, sync only runs sync steps.  It doesn't make sense for install to run both install and sync steps.

commits.commitMessage:
Rework project layout

- Move setup.py at project root
- Move resources in a single folder (extensions, man, shared files)
  - leaf-shell unit test now works
- Automatic data files list in setup.py
- Rework test with setup.py, nosetests & tox
- Update debian package script
- Update Docker image
- Add python 37 support tests
- Add "venv" target in Makefile to init a viirtualenv with requirements

Change-Id: Id63ce625497835e65ad03ebb4c079bd1f0ecc708
Resolves: LETOOLS-418
commits.subject: Rework project layout

Fix package install from profile and overides

If a profile is tweaked to set a dynamic dependency and this package is
overriden at the same time, the original verison is not installed which
leads to inconsistent install & sync.

commits.commitMessage:
Performance issue to detect external commands

To get the description from an external commands, leaf was executing the
file with --description arguments.
This was causing some performance issues since many of our extensions
are written in python and the python vm is fast but ran X times, it
create a latency.

So now the description must be in the 2048 first bytes of the file,
after the motif LEAF_DESCRIPTION.

Change-Id: I331d36a015bc8a27eca35bfc23ff799a8ac7ef77
Resolves: LETOOLS-409
commits.subject: Performance issue to detect external commands

commits.commitMessage:
Integrate a Shell Command into Leaf

Provide more complete integration between Leaf and a sub-shell.

Leaf shell is implemented as an external command.  Additionally, the
handling of each supported shell type is handled by a subscript that
is written to know the details of that shell.

Supported shells are Bash and Zsh.

Extra config variables:

LEAF_SHELL_PROMPT_PREFIX   -- This defaults to lsh and is always
                              appended to the prompt.

LEAF_SHELL_ZSH_PROMPT_SIDE -- If set to the value 'right' makes this
                              support script append the Leaf prompt
                              info on the righthand side.  To reset
                              it back to the left, simply unset the
                              variable.

Resolves: LETOOLS-347
Change-Id: Ib3488ab7344ef07ee794429b66ffce00860446b9
commits.subject: Integrate a Shell Command into Leaf

comments.message: I think I need to turn on my Vim spellchecker again!
Seems like this would force users to use bash, while we are quite a few using zsh instead of bash, which is mostly compatible with bash for quite a lot of things.

Maybe for the zsh support, you can just do a symlink from leafsh.zsh.sh to leafsh.bash.sh, and switch the command that is being launched based on the current script name.

BTW https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2727172/how-to-load-different-zshrc-file-via-commandline-option

So that would be exec zsh --rcs /usr/share/leaf/leafsh.bashrc.sh

The idea is that we provide a separate script:

    leafsh.zsh.sh

That does similar integration with zsh.

I've added a `leaf shell` command to leaf that will search for a script for the current shell, and if it can't find one it will default to bash.

In an update to this patch, I'd like to look at supporting other shells.
It's a differnt form of different!

Only apt-get install is supported here, and apt-get in default prefix.

But, maybe it makes sense to enforce this limitation and if people complain, we can look at supporting recursive shells properly.  Ok, I'll modify the code.

Leaf uses the pathlib API to handle path which is nice, 
script = Path("some/path") / "folder" / "another"
and you have script.is_file() .exists() ...
See https://docs.python.org/3.4/library/pathlib.html

Ok, I changed it to get the path from the leaf constants.  I just need to figure out how to tell how we were installed and what the path should be.
The logger should be used to print messages

Right.  I'll fix that.  I had it in an earlier version, I must have missed it in the refactor.
useless as soon as leaf-shell will be moved to src/extensions
Any variables that you have defined at the leaf user|workspace|profile level are available to you in the leaf shell.
I've been trying to capatialize when I'm using Leaf as a name, and all lower case when I'm using Leaf as a command.  Same with Bash and Zsh.

Until now, we tried to keep the leaf documentation as generic as possible.
This kind of example should be part of legato specific workflow help pages, that would be contributed in another Gerrit repository
No need to add these lines
Another patch removes these lines, so I was trying to not conflict with it here.
No need to add these lines

Do we need to export (will be in user env at the end) error messages?

More thant 10 LEAF_SHELL_XXX variables are exported in the final user env.
I'm not saying this is a problem, but do we need to *export* all of them?
Zsh theming uses local variables which are not exported.
I don't understand why we need the user to copy the skel bashrc?
The .bashrc was not found.  This is a helpful message for how to create a new one from the system default.

Ok, this file has to be named .zshrc due to zsh.
But bashrc does not need to.

I'm not confortable with hidden code in git repository.
I first got your patch using git, and did'nt even saw these files.

So I would propose to rename both .zsh/.barh rc to zsh/bash rc and make a symlink only for zsh as bash works with non hidden file, to see if that work?

I'm hitting a problem where you need to use sudo to create the link.

I'd prefer to keep the files the same for consistency.
We should have a look to ZDOTDIR instead of assuming $HOME/.zshrc
I've looked at this and apparently $ZDOTDIR isn't always set, and it looks like the convention is to use $HOME if $ZDOTDIR isn't set.  So that's the approach I'm taking here.

Why don't you use it on line 26?

As we name the feature *shell*, shouldn't we implement args like shells (bash, zsh) expecting a -c if the user wants to execute a command? 
leaf shell -c make 

It makes more sense to me

If I use -c then the shell becomes a non-interactive shell.

Non-Interactive shells do *not* evaluate rc files anymore, so none of the integration would be available to that shell.

As it is today, if the user does a:

  $ leaf shell -c "make install"

Everything works as expected.  They can even use a non-default shell, for example on my system Bash is the default:

  $ leaf shell -n zsh -c "make install"

We should delete files once used to keep a consistent workflow.
Once a env is unloaded, no need to do it twice, it will be inconsistent, removing the file once done looks safer.

David has already argued that it would be more convenient to not delete these files so that they're available for potential debugging.

That's why I removed the code that clears out these files on shell shutdown.

We just need to all agree if we are deleting these files or not.
If we agree to clean up these files, then I can add the automatic cleanup back into the script.

Indeed there is no need to clean up the temporary files when exiting from the shell.
What is pointed out here is that, as the presence of the deactivate file is the trigger for environment unload, this file must be cleaned once we've sourced it, so that we don't enter into the if a second time (and more).

That shebang is not recommended, 

#!/usr/bin/env python3

variable name SHARED_FOLDER could be more relevant

And as this folder won't contain only files for extensions should be renamed SETUP_FOLDER / "shared". More generic name and not in "extensions" folder.

Let's keep it generic in usr/leaf
And prefix all leaf-shell files with lsh or leaf-shell
the rendering with quotes is not that good (look to be somehow interpreted in the man page generation); remove?
Should be removed; I don't think there will be a conflict now.

Sebastien comments on Patch 10 still need to be implemented
(cf https://gerrit-legato/#/c/leaf/+/28660/10/src/setup.py)
change by "python3 -m leaf XXX" to make it compatible both with tests and installed environment
Indeed extensions tests can't work at the moment because of the way tests are executed. Working on it at the moment.

env-A test package is exporting a "LEAF_ENV_A": "FOO" variable.
What about testing the value with leaf shell to verify that all is set correctly?
Something like:

self.leafExec("shell", "-c", "test \$LEAF_ENV_A = FOO")


(Same for the two following lines)

I was planning on doing something like that, but I could never get the test to work.

Also, I couldn't run docker on my PC, it told me I didn't have permission for the image, or that it didn't exist.

change has just been merged on master to have tests running well for extensions. This is just requiring extensions to call leaf via "python3 -m leaf" rather than directly through the leaf executable (because this one is not yet generated at test time) -- cf my other comment on leafsh.common.sh

If you rebase your dev on master, this will help.
Considering docker, please make sure that:
* your current user belong to the "docker" group
* you do a "make docker-build" before doing a make "docker-test"

@Sarra, @Chloe
As a reminder, the purpose of this change is to implement a missing behavior.
Until today, in the leaf-data tree of a profile, there was no management of "overriding" a package version by another.
If the same package was referenced with different versions in a same given profile, the leaf-data tree was containing the two versions.

This patch fixes this.
There is no interface impact as such.

commits.commitMessage:
Adding "latest" dependency resolution for profiles

- When building the dependency list, there are 2 strategies
  - "all versions": current implementation
  - "latest": if the same packages with n versions exists in a solved
    dependency list, use the latest everywhere it is needed
- For package operations (ex: leaf pkg env), "all versions" stragegy is
  used
- For workspace operations (ex: leaf env), "latest" stragegy is used.
  Which mean a package from a container can be overriden with a newer
  version in a profile
- Unit tests

Change-Id: I6cd29cc93c9a1c198ffe40d3eeb886515c1c49c7
Resolves: LETOOLS-366
commits.subject: Adding "latest" dependency resolution for profiles

comments.message: in an "else" of the if test above, shouldn't we reset LEAF_PROFILE to "no profile"?
actually, would be useless, as already managed by the deactivate script (which will reset the profile to its initial value ("no profile") rather that simply unseting it)
Can you please update the commit message to point to the right ticket?
we shouldn't be calling this foo.  It should be meaningful to the example.  leaf-helloWorld maybe? or leaf-sample?

I didn't want to use sample or demo as these keywords could easily be external commands in the future.
I opted for mycommand.

It shouldn't be foo or bar.. I've been trying to remove these from all the code.  foobar is derivative for fubar, which means "fucked up beyond all recognition" and it's not something that we want to be promoting in our code even if it is developer slang and convention.

Thanks for the explanation, I wasn't aware at all :)
I'll try (because I use foo a lot) to switch to another words.
tw (trailing whitespace) it need to all be removed.

commits.commitMessage:
Add bash completion

- Use argcomplete to automatically generate bash completion
- Parse --help for command list
- Add bashcompinit for zsh compatibility

Resolves: LETOOLS-3
Change-Id: I1c2971b1bf1ba12a6dc989aaa284a68c0073398a
commits.subject: Add bash completion

comments.message: we should parse commands from `leaf --help`, in order to support as well commands coming from extensions, dynamically

There's a python module, argcomplete that lets you hook bash completion right up to the argparse lib.

   https://argcomplete.readthedocs.io/en/latest/

Using this method it is really easy to keep the completion up to date with the latest version of Leaf.

Special handling for looking up profiles or other completion tasks is completely written in Python.

Basic handling is setup by adding the line:

    argcomplete.autocomplete(parser)

After all of the calls to:

    parser.add_argument

and before the call to:

    parser.parse_args()

We really should use something like this instead of hand writing the completion.

Good idea.
I'm looking to use argcomplete.
It introduces a new dependency and is only compatible with bash at the moment, but it may be worth it.

Add this before the `complete -F` command to support zsh.
```
# zsh compatibility
if [ -n "$ZSH_VERSION" ]; then
    autoload bashcompinit
    bashcompinit
fi
```

I also use zsh, but bash was the first step.
Zsh is the next step, and thanks for the snippet, I didn't know about bashcompinit, it makes it quite easy ;)

Patch Set 2:

The exec sounds like a good idea, thanks for pointing this out.

But from a linux user point of view I wouldn't like leaf of whatever the tool I use to modify my bash configuration. 
(Or zsh, I use zsh which by the way handles history way better than bash, ant that is not the only advantage.)
I manage my dotfiles in a git repository to be sure of the content, finding that leaf alters it could give a bad impression for newcommers.

I personnally see the shell as an entry point to profiles, but I would definitly promote the eval `leaf env` way to keep the same shell and avoid history & $PS1 issues we can have spawning a shell.
Because if a profile (or a sdk) export PS1="($LEAF_PROFILE) $PS1", running eval `leaf env` add the profile name to your prompt, which does not work when you span a shell (PS1 is set in bash/zsh rc files).

comments.message:
How about we change:

   $SHELL "$@"

to
    export $SHELL "$@"


So that the new shell process replaces the sh process, and we don't have "dead" processes hanging around in the background.

Also, a huge complaint that people have with sub-shells is that they loose history on that sub-shell startup, so how about we add or put a recommendation in our docs for the following to be put in the user's .bashrc:  Or we can automatally append this in the users .bashrc when leaf is installed.


    # Tell Bash to append to the history file and not overwrite it.
    shopt -s histappend

    # A function that forces a history flush before the sub-command is run, and then
    # tells Bash to refresh the history after the command completes.
    #
    # When the command is a sub-shell, then your current history is now able to be
    # imported into the new sub-shell.  On return the new history is refreshed into
    # the current shell.
    function RefreshHistory
    {
        history -a
        $@
        history -r
    }

    # This function will run leaf, and when running a sub-shell it will
    # preserve command history across the two shells.
    function LeafHistory
    {
        subCommand=$1

        if [ "$subCommand" == "sh" ]
        then
            history leaf $@
        else
            leaf $@
        fi
    }

    # Alias leaf's sub-command for launching shells so that our current
    # shell instance can refresh it's history when running a leaf sub-shell:
    alias leaf='LeafHistory`

Sorry this should have been:

How about we change:

    $SHELL "$@"

to
    exec $SHELL "$@"

I wonder what is the better UX:
* allowing people to switch between profiles in the same terminal
* forcing them to open several terminals as soon as they want to play with multiple profiles

Maybe that's because we didn't though about it until you made that suggestion, but my preference would go to first solution...

Totally, I don't want to force people to change terminals.

Allowing people to use the "top-level" commands like the mksys wrappers allows us to not force people to setup their environment.  They just change into a project directory and type mksys.

However, 

   leaf sh

Is also a powerful tool that I wouldn't want to discount.

With the top level tools and having leaf sh we can enable many different work styles.

Perhaps we could package up the shell code in a " leaf-util.sh" that we could tell people to source in their bashrc if they want to enable the history preserving features?

Oh I made a typeo in my code, in the my function LeafHistory change

    history leaf $@

to

    RefreshHistory leaf $@
